transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for participating in this interview. I'm going to ask you some questions about your health and experiences. Let's begin.

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Hello, thank you for having me. I'm glad to participate in this interview. I'm ready to answer your questions. 

1. To start, can you tell me about your overall health and any specific health concerns you may have?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me a bit about yourself and your current life situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Grace: Of course. As I mentioned, I'm 55 years old and I live in rural Montana. I recently retired from teaching, which I did for over 30 years. I enjoyed my time in the classroom, but now I'm focusing on my health and personal interests. I’m widowed, and I have two grown children who live nearby. 

In terms of my health, I consider myself quite health-conscious. I exercise regularly, and I manage my type 2 diabetes fairly well. However, I do have some concerns, particularly with my weight and a recent diagnosis of anemia. I also have prediabetes, which I’m trying to address through diet and exercise. 

While I’m generally healthy, I do find that maintaining my health can be a bit challenging, especially with my obesity and the issues related to it. I’m aware that I need to stay proactive about my health to prevent any complications. 

I also have some feelings about my living situation; I feel that my housing is not quite satisfactory, which sometimes adds to my stress levels. Overall, I’m focused on staying active and managing my health as best as I can.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your pregnancy or pregnancies? When did you first learn you were pregnant?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Grace: I had two pregnancies, both of which were quite straightforward. I learned I was pregnant for the first time when I was in my late twenties. I remember feeling a mix of excitement and nervousness. It was a joyful time, and I was fortunate to have a supportive partner by my side.

My first pregnancy went smoothly, and I delivered a healthy baby girl. A few years later, I became pregnant again, and I had another wonderful experience, giving birth to my son. Both pregnancies were vaginal deliveries, and I took great care of myself during that time, focusing on nutrition and regular check-ups.

Since then, I've been very aware of my reproductive health, but I’m not planning on having any more children. I've been using hormonal contraception to manage that aspect of my health. Looking back, I feel grateful for the experiences, but I also recognize that the pregnancies did come with their own set of challenges, especially in terms of physical changes and managing my overall health afterwards. 

Is there anything specific you would like to know about my pregnancies or experiences during that time?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: When did you first seek prenatal care? What was that experience like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Grace: I started seeking prenatal care as soon as I confirmed my pregnancies. For my first pregnancy, I remember scheduling my first appointment with my obstetrician shortly after taking a home pregnancy test. It was important to me to ensure that I was doing everything right for my baby. 

The experience was largely positive. My doctor was very supportive and took the time to answer all of my questions, which helped ease my nerves. I had regular check-ups throughout the pregnancy, and I appreciated the attention to my health and the baby’s development. 

I was given guidance on nutrition, exercise, and what to expect during pregnancy, which made me feel more prepared. There were moments when I felt overwhelmed by all the changes happening to my body, but having that support and care made a significant difference.

For my second pregnancy, I sought care even earlier, as I had a better understanding of what to expect. The experience was similar; I felt well-supported throughout and was able to share my previous experiences and concerns with my healthcare provider.

Overall, I felt that prenatal care was vital for my peace of mind and for ensuring that both my babies were healthy. Would you like to know more about any specific aspects of my prenatal care?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who is providing your prenatal care? Can you describe your relationship with your healthcare provider?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Grace: Since I’m no longer pregnant, I’m not currently receiving prenatal care. However, during my pregnancies, I was under the care of a wonderful obstetrician. I felt very fortunate to have a provider who not only was knowledgeable but also genuinely cared about my well-being and that of my babies. 

I built a trusting relationship with my obstetrician, which was essential for me. I could share my concerns openly, and I always felt heard and respected. I appreciated how they took the time to explain things and involve me in decisions regarding my care. This made me feel empowered as a patient. 

The office staff was also supportive, which contributed to a positive experience overall. Even though I was nervous at times, the environment felt welcoming, and the healthcare team was attentive to my needs. 

Now that I’m focusing on my overall health, I see a primary care physician who helps me manage my diabetes and other health issues. I still maintain that same level of communication and trust with my current healthcare provider, which is important to me. Is there anything specific you’d like to know about my relationship with my healthcare providers or the care I received?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How often do you have prenatal appointments? Can you walk me through what a typical visit is like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Grace: Since I’m no longer pregnant, I don’t have prenatal appointments anymore. However, I can tell you about what my typical visits were like during my pregnancies. 

I generally had monthly appointments in the first and second trimesters, which increased to biweekly and then weekly as I approached my due date. Each visit usually began with a check-in about how I was feeling. The healthcare provider would take my weight, check my blood pressure, and listen to the baby’s heartbeat, which was always a highlight for me. 

Then we would discuss any concerns I had, whether they were physical discomforts, questions about nutrition, or what to expect in the coming weeks. My doctor would often provide information on the development of the baby and any necessary tests or screenings that were due. I appreciated how they took the time to explain the purpose of each test and what the results might mean.

Ultrasounds were also part of the visits, especially in the second trimester, and I loved seeing my baby on the screen. It was an emotional experience for me. I felt like every appointment was an opportunity to connect with my baby and ensure everything was progressing well.

The visits lasted anywhere from 30 minutes to an hour, depending on how many questions I had and if any additional procedures were necessary. I always left feeling more informed and reassured. 

Now, I have regular appointments with my primary care physician to manage my diabetes and anemia, and they involve similar check-ins about my health and any ongoing concerns. Would you like to know more about the types of tests or screenings I had during my pregnancies?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you experienced any health concerns or complications during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Grace: During my pregnancies, I was fortunate to have relatively few complications. However, I did experience some common discomforts, such as morning sickness in the first trimester and some back pain as I approached my due dates. My healthcare provider reassured me that these were normal experiences, which helped ease my concerns.

One specific health concern I faced during my second pregnancy was slightly elevated blood pressure, which my doctor monitored closely. They discussed the importance of stress management and staying active, which I found helpful. Thankfully, it was managed well, and I didn’t experience any significant complications.

I was also aware of my weight gain during both pregnancies, especially since I was already dealing with obesity. My doctor provided guidance on maintaining a healthy diet and staying active, but I sometimes struggled to balance that with cravings and the changes my body was going through. 

Overall, while there were challenges, I felt supported by my healthcare team, which made a significant difference in how I managed those concerns. 

Do you have any specific questions about my experiences with complications or health issues during my pregnancies?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What medications or supplements are you currently taking?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Grace: Currently, I take a few medications and supplements to help manage my health. For my type 2 diabetes, I'm on metformin, which helps control my blood sugar levels. I've found it to be effective, and my healthcare provider monitors my blood sugar regularly to ensure everything stays within a healthy range.

In addition to that, I've been prescribed iron supplements to address my anemia. My doctor recommended these because my iron levels were low, and they suggested focusing on both dietary sources and supplementation to improve my overall health.

I also take a daily multivitamin to support my general well-being, especially considering my age and the physical changes I've experienced as a result of my weight and diabetes. I try to maintain a balanced diet, but I believe that these supplements help fill any nutritional gaps.

Finally, I’ve been advised to take vitamin D, especially since I live in a rural area where sunlight exposure can be limited during the winter months. 

If you’d like to know more about how I manage my medications or any specific dietary changes I've made, I’d be happy to share!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your diet and nutrition during pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Grace: During my pregnancies, I was very conscious of my diet and nutrition. I wanted to ensure that I was providing the best possible environment for my babies to grow and develop. 

In the early stages, I focused on maintaining a balanced diet that included a variety of fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats. I was aware of the importance of folic acid, so I made sure to include foods like leafy greens, beans, and fortified cereals in my meals. 

As my pregnancies progressed, I tried to pay attention to my caloric intake, especially since I was dealing with obesity. I worked with my healthcare provider to create meal plans that would help me gain weight at a healthy rate while also managing my blood sugar levels, given my history of prediabetes. 

I did experience some challenges, especially with cravings. There were times when I craved sweets or comfort foods, and while I allowed myself to indulge occasionally, I tried to balance those with healthier options. My doctor encouraged me to listen to my body and not to deprive myself completely, which helped me maintain a healthier mindset about eating.

I also made sure to stay hydrated, which is so important during pregnancy. I aimed to drink plenty of water and limit sugary drinks. 

Overall, I felt that my focus on nutrition was beneficial not just for my babies’ health, but also for my own well-being. Looking back, I’m proud of the effort I put into my diet during that time. 

Is there anything specific you’d like to know about my dietary choices or how I balanced my nutrition with my health concerns during pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How have you been feeling emotionally during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Grace: Emotionally, my pregnancies were a mix of excitement and anxiety, which is completely normal, I believe. I remember feeling an overwhelming sense of joy when I first learned I was pregnant, but there were also moments of worry about the health of my babies and how I would manage the physical and emotional changes.

During my first pregnancy, I was generally optimistic, but I did experience some anxiety about being a new mother and whether I would be able to handle the responsibilities that came with it. I often sought reassurance from my healthcare provider, which helped alleviate some of my fears. My partner was incredibly supportive, and that made a big difference in how I processed my emotions.

With my second pregnancy, I felt a bit more prepared, but there were still moments of stress. I was balancing my job as a teacher with preparing for the arrival of my son, and sometimes that felt overwhelming. I found that practicing mindfulness and taking time for myself helped me cope with the stress. I also leaned on my friends and family for support, and that was invaluable.

Overall, I’d say I experienced the full range of emotions during my pregnancies, but I always felt that being proactive about my health and maintaining open communication with my healthcare provider helped me navigate those feelings. 

If you have any specific questions about how I managed my emotional health during pregnancy or if you’d like to know more about the support systems I had in place, feel free to ask!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who supports you during your pregnancy? Can you tell me about your support network?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Grace: During my pregnancies, I was fortunate to have a strong support network that made a significant difference in my experience. First and foremost, my partner was my biggest source of support. He was always there for me, attending appointments, helping with preparations, and just being a reassuring presence. His encouragement helped me feel more confident and less anxious about the changes I was going through.

In addition to my partner, I had a close group of friends who were also mothers. They provided invaluable advice and emotional support, sharing their own experiences and tips on everything from pregnancy discomforts to newborn care. I appreciated having people who understood what I was going through, and we often met up to talk and share our journeys.

My family was also very supportive, especially my parents. They were always ready to help whenever I needed it, whether it was running errands or just being there to listen when I needed to vent. Knowing that they were just a phone call away gave me peace of mind.

Furthermore, I had a wonderful relationship with my healthcare provider, which I mentioned earlier. I felt comfortable discussing my concerns and emotions with them, and they provided reassurance and guidance that helped me navigate the ups and downs of pregnancy.

Overall, the combination of my partner, friends, family, and healthcare provider created a robust support system that helped me feel grounded during my pregnancies. If you’d like to know more about how specific individuals helped me or any particular situations where support made a difference, I’d be happy to share!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about your birth plan? What are your preferences for delivery?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Grace: Yes, I did think about my birth plan during both of my pregnancies. For my first pregnancy, I wanted to have a natural vaginal delivery, and that was ultimately how it went. I had done some research and talked with my healthcare provider about pain management options, but I was open to going with the flow.

I had preferences for the environment as well; I wanted a calm and supportive atmosphere in the delivery room, and I was fortunate to have that. My partner was there with me, and I wanted him to be actively involved, helping to coach me through the process.

For my second pregnancy, I had a clearer idea of what to expect since I had gone through it before. I still preferred a natural delivery, and I felt more confident in communicating my wishes to my healthcare provider. I also wanted to try some different comfort techniques, like breathing exercises and movement during labor, which I found helpful the first time around.

I was very focused on minimizing interventions unless absolutely necessary, and I appreciated that my healthcare provider respected my wishes while also keeping an eye on my and my baby's health. Thankfully, both of my deliveries went smoothly, and I felt well-supported throughout the entire process.

Looking back, I feel grateful that my preferences were taken into account, and I was able to have the positive birth experiences I hoped for. If you’d like to know more about any specific aspects of my birth plan or how I prepared for delivery, feel free to ask!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What sources of information have you used to learn about pregnancy and childbirth?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Grace: During my pregnancies, I utilized a variety of sources to learn about pregnancy and childbirth. I started with books, especially those recommended by my healthcare provider. One of my favorites was "What to Expect When You're Expecting," as it provided a comprehensive overview of each stage of pregnancy and addressed numerous questions and concerns I had.

In addition to books, I found online resources to be incredibly helpful. Websites like the American Pregnancy Association and the Mayo Clinic offered reliable information on pregnancy health, nutrition, and labor preparation. I made sure to choose reputable sources to ensure I was getting accurate and up-to-date information.

I also attended prenatal classes, which I found invaluable. These classes not only covered the basics of pregnancy, childbirth, and newborn care, but they also provided a space for me to connect with other expectant mothers. Sharing experiences with others in similar situations really helped me feel less isolated.

Furthermore, I often consulted with my healthcare provider during my prenatal appointments. They were a fantastic resource for answering my questions, addressing my concerns, and providing personalized advice based on my health history. I appreciated their willingness to take the time to educate me and ensure I felt prepared.

Lastly, I leaned on my friends and family, especially those who had already been through the process of pregnancy and childbirth. Their firsthand experiences and tips were incredibly valuable and comforting.

Looking back, I believe that gathering information from these various sources helped me feel more empowered and prepared for the journey of pregnancy and childbirth. If you’re interested in specific resources I found particularly helpful or any other aspects of how I gathered information, I’d be happy to share!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How are you managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Grace: Since I’m no longer pregnant, I can share how I managed the financial aspects during my pregnancies. At the time, I was fortunate to have health insurance coverage through Medicare, which helped alleviate some of the financial burden associated with prenatal care and delivery. 

I made sure to keep track of all my medical appointments and the associated costs, including laboratory tests and ultrasounds. I was proactive in discussing the coverage details with my healthcare provider and the billing department to understand what was covered and what I might need to pay out-of-pocket.

In addition to medical expenses, I also budgeted for items related to preparing for the baby, such as maternity clothes, baby gear, and nursery essentials. I was conscious of my spending and tried to prioritize necessary items while also seeking out sales or second-hand options. I found that many of my friends and family offered hand-me-downs, which was very helpful and saved some money.

I also created a savings plan to set aside funds for unexpected expenses that might arise during pregnancy or after the baby’s arrival. This gave me peace of mind, knowing that I had some financial cushion in case of emergencies.

Overall, while I did face some financial considerations during my pregnancies, having a solid support system and health coverage helped me manage those aspects effectively. If you’d like to know more about specific budgeting strategies I used or any other financial concerns related to my pregnancies, feel free to ask!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How has your pregnancy affected your work or employment situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Grace: During my pregnancies, I was actively working as a teacher, and I found that balancing my job with the demands of pregnancy required careful planning and communication. 

Initially, when I confirmed my first pregnancy, I felt a mix of excitement and concern about how it would affect my work. I loved my job and was committed to my students, but I also knew that pregnancy would bring physical and emotional changes. I decided to inform my principal early on, so we could discuss my schedule and any necessary accommodations.

Throughout my first pregnancy, I was fortunate that my school was supportive. They allowed me to adjust my workload as needed, especially during periods of fatigue or discomfort. I also made sure to take regular breaks during the day to rest and stay hydrated, which helped me manage my energy levels.

When it came to my second pregnancy, I felt more confident in advocating for myself. I had learned from my first experience, and I was proactive in discussing my needs with my colleagues and administration. I set boundaries to ensure that I was not overextending myself and communicated openly with my students about my pregnancy, which helped them understand any adjustments in my teaching style or schedule.

As I approached my due date, I made arrangements for my maternity leave well in advance. I worked closely with my principal to ensure a smooth transition for both my students and the substitute teacher who would take over my classes. This planning was crucial for me, as it alleviated concerns about my responsibilities and allowed me to focus on preparing for the arrival of my babies.

Overall, while my pregnancies did require some adjustments to my work routine, I felt fortunate to have a supportive work environment that valued my well-being. If you're interested in how I managed specific challenges at work or any other aspects of balancing my job and pregnancy, I’d be happy to share!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about the postpartum period? What plans do you have for after the baby arrives?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Grace: Yes, I definitely thought about the postpartum period during my pregnancies. I knew that it would be a critical time for both recovery and bonding with my new baby. I wanted to ensure that I had a plan in place to support my physical and emotional well-being after delivery.

One of my main focuses was on recovery. I made sure to discuss with my healthcare provider what to expect in terms of physical changes and healing after childbirth. I wanted to be prepared for things like fatigue, breastfeeding challenges, and any physical discomfort I might experience.

I also recognized the importance of having a support system in place. I planned to lean on my partner, family, and friends during the postpartum period. I had conversations with them ahead of time, letting them know how they could assist me, whether it was helping with household chores, cooking meals, or simply providing emotional support. I felt that having that support network would be crucial for my mental health as I adjusted to new motherhood.

In addition to that, I made plans to prioritize self-care. I knew that taking care of myself would help me be a better mother. I intended to carve out time for rest, even if it was short naps during the day while the baby napped. I also wanted to stay active when possible, as I found that exercise helped boost my mood and energy levels.

I was also aware of the potential for postpartum anxiety or depression, so I made a point to stay connected with my healthcare provider for any concerns that might arise. I felt it was important to have open communication about my emotional health and any challenges I faced.

Overall, I aimed to approach the postpartum period with a mindset of flexibility and self-compassion, recognizing that it would be a significant transition. If you’d like to know more about specific strategies I planned for the postpartum period or any other aspects of my preparation, I’d be happy to share!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Thank you for your time and for sharing your experiences with me. This concludes our interview.
